Power system modelling

The dynamics of the power system with the change in power (ΔP) as input and the change in frequency (Δf) as output is given by:
14Gs=ΔfΔP=1D+Ms\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ G(s)=\frac{\Delta f}{\Delta P}=\frac{1}{D+ Ms} $$\end{document}

Minimization of frequency fluctuation (∆f) along with the controller output (∆u) is the objective function and can be depicted by integral square error (ISE) given as:
15J=∫0TΔf2+Δu2/kdt\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ J=\underset{0}{\overset{T}{\int }}\left[{\left(\Delta f\right)}^2+{\left(\Delta u\right)}^2/k\right] dt $$\end{document}where k is selected as 5 to give both parts in (15) the same weight in the course of the optimization process. The SGWO method is engaged to tune the PID gains and the SFs of the AFPID controller. The ∆f and ∆u signal have least J value for the efficient performance of the DPGS.

